# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: http-strict-transport-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:http-strict-transport-security/glossary-hsts] In other words, it tells the browser that changing the protocol from HTTP to HTTPS in a URL works (and is more secure) and asks the browser to do it for every request.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS Policy is communicated by the server to the user agent via an HTTP response header field named `Strict-Transport-Security`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS Policy specifies a period of time during which the user agent should only access the server in a secure fashion.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Websites using HSTS often do not accept clear text HTTP, either by rejecting connections over HTTP or systematically redirecting users to HTTPS (though this is not required by the specification).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The consequence of this is that a user-agent not capable of doing TLS will not be able to connect to the site.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The protection normally only applies after a user has visited the site at least once, relying on the principle of "trust on first use".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The way this protection works is that when a user entering or selecting an HTTP (not HTTPS) URL to the site, the client, such as a Web browser, will automatically upgrade to HTTPS without making an HTTP request, thereby preventing any HTTP man-in-the-middle attack from occurring.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] To counteract this problem, an HSTS preload list maintained by Google Chrome and used by other major web browsers is maintained.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] If a domain is on this list, the browser skips the initial request and encrypts all communication immediately.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Additional domains can be registered at no cost.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS specification was published as RFC 6797 on 19 November 2012 after being approved on 2 October 2012 by the IESG for publication as a Proposed Standard RFC.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The authors originally submitted it as an Internet Draft on 17 June 2010.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] With the conversion to an Internet Draft, the specification name was altered from "Strict Transport Security" (STS) to "HTTP Strict Transport Security", because the specification applies only to HTTP.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HTTP response header field defined in the HSTS specification however remains named "Strict-Transport-Security".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The last so-called "community version" of the then-named "STS" specification was published on 18 December 2009, with revisions based on community feedback.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The original draft specification by Jeff Hodges from PayPal, Collin Jackson, and Adam Barth was published on 18 September 2009.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS specification is based on original work by Jackson and Barth as described in their paper "ForceHTTPS: Protecting High-Security Web Sites from Network Attacks".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Additionally, HSTS is the realization of one facet of an overall vision for improving web security, put forward by Jeff Hodges and Andy Steingruebl in their 2010 paper *The Need for Coherent Web Security Policy Framework(s)*.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] A server implements an HSTS policy by supplying a header over an HTTPS connection (HSTS headers over HTTP are ignored).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] For example, a server could send a header such that future requests to the domain for the next year (max-age is specified in seconds; 31,536,000 is equal to one non-leap year) use only HTTPS: `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] If the security of the connection cannot be ensured (e.g. the server's TLS certificate is not trusted), the user agent must terminate the connection and should not allow the user to access the web application.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] This helps protect web application users against some passive (eavesdropping) and active network attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] A man-in-the-middle attacker has a greatly reduced ability to intercept requests and responses between a user and a web application server while the user's browser has HSTS Policy in effect for that web application.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The most important security vulnerability that HSTS can fix is SSL-stripping man-in-the-middle attacks, first publicly introduced by Moxie Marlinspike in his 2009 BlackHat Federal talk "New Tricks For Defeating SSL In Practice".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The SSL (and TLS) stripping attack works by transparently converting a secure HTTPS connection into a plain HTTP connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The user can see that the connection is insecure, but crucially there is no way of knowing whether the connection *should* be secure.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] At the time of Marlinspike's talk, many websites did not use TLS/SSL, therefore there was no way of knowing (without prior knowledge) whether the use of plain HTTP was due to an attack, or simply because the website had not implemented TLS/SSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Additionally, no warnings are presented to the user during the downgrade process, making the attack fairly subtle to all but the most vigilant.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Marlinspike's sslstrip tool, presented at Black Hat DC 2009, fully automates the attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS addresses this problem by informing the browser that connections to the site should always use TLS/SSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The HSTS header can be stripped by the attacker if this is the user's first visit.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Microsoft Edge attempt to limit this problem by including a "pre-loaded" list of HSTS sites.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Unfortunately this solution cannot scale to include all websites on the internet.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS can also help to prevent having one's cookie-based website login credentials stolen by widely available tools such as Firesheep.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Because HSTS is time limited, it is sensitive to attacks involving shifting the victim's computer time e.g. using false NTP packets.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The initial request remains unprotected from active attacks if it uses an insecure protocol such as plain HTTP or if the URI for the initial request was obtained over an insecure channel.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] The same applies to the first request after the activity period specified in the advertised HSTS Policy `max-age` (sites should set a period of several days or months depending on user activity and behavior).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, and Internet Explorer/Microsoft Edge address this limitation by implementing a "HSTS preloaded list", which is a list that contains known sites supporting HSTS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] This list is distributed with the browser so that it uses HTTPS for the initial request to the listed sites as well.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] As previously mentioned, these pre-loaded lists cannot scale to cover the entire Web.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] A potential solution might be achieved by using DNS records to declare HSTS Policy, and accessing them securely via DNSSEC, optionally with certificate fingerprints to ensure validity (which requires running a validating resolver to avoid last mile issues).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Even with an HSTS preloaded list, HSTS cannot prevent advanced attacks against TLS itself, such as the BEAST or CRIME attacks introduced by Juliano Rizzo and Thai Duong.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Attacks against TLS itself are orthogonal to HSTS policy enforcement.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Neither can it protect against attacks on the server - if someone compromises it, it will happily serve any content over TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] HSTS can be used to near-indelibly tag visiting browsers with recoverable identifying data (supercookies) which can persist in and out of browser "incognito" privacy modes.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] By creating a web page that makes multiple HTTP requests to selected domains, for example, if twenty browser requests to twenty different domains are used, theoretically over one million visitors can be distinguished (220) due to the resulting requests arriving via HTTP vs.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] HTTPS; the latter being the previously recorded binary "bits" established earlier via HSTS headers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/http-strict-transport-security] Depending on the actual deployment there are certain threats (e.g. cookie injection attacks) that can be avoided by following best practices.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The principal motivations for HTTPS are authentication of the accessed website and protection of the privacy and integrity of the exchanged data while it is in transit.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] It protects against man-in-the-middle attacks, and the bidirectional block cipher encryption of communications between a client and server protects the communications against eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The authentication aspect of HTTPS requires a trusted third party to sign server-side digital certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This was historically an expensive operation, which meant fully authenticated HTTPS connections were usually found only on secured payment transaction services and other secured corporate information systems on the World Wide Web.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] In 2016, a campaign by the Electronic Frontier Foundation with the support of web browser developers led to the protocol becoming more prevalent.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS has since 2018 been used more often by web users than non-secure HTTP, primarily to protect page authenticity on all types of websites, secure accounts, and keep user communications, identity, and web browsing private.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) scheme *HTTPS* has identical usage syntax to the HTTP scheme.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] However, HTTPS signals the browser to use an added encryption layer of SSL/TLS to protect the traffic.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] SSL/TLS is especially suited for HTTP, since it can provide some protection even if only one side of the communication is authenticated.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This is the case with HTTP transactions over the Internet, where typically only the server is authenticated (by the client examining the server's certificate).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS creates a secure channel over an insecure network.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This ensures reasonable protection from eavesdroppers and man-in-the-middle attacks, provided that adequate cipher suites are used and that the server certificate is verified and trusted.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Because HTTPS piggybacks HTTP entirely on top of TLS, the entirety of the underlying HTTP protocol can be encrypted.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This includes the request's URL, query parameters, headers, and cookies (which often contain identifying information about the user).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] However, because website addresses and port numbers are necessarily part of the underlying TCP/IP protocols, HTTPS cannot protect their disclosure.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Web browsers know how to trust HTTPS websites based on certificate authorities that come pre-installed in their software.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Certificate authorities are in this way being trusted by web browser creators to provide valid certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS is especially important over insecure networks and networks that may be subject to tampering.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Insecure networks, such as public Wi-Fi access points, allow anyone on the same local network to packet-sniff and discover sensitive information not protected by HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Additionally, some free-to-use and paid WLAN networks have been observed tampering with webpages by engaging in packet injection in order to serve their own ads on other websites.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This practice can be exploited maliciously in many ways, such as by injecting malware onto webpages and stealing users' private information.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS is also important for connections over the Tor network, as malicious Tor nodes could otherwise damage or alter the contents passing through them in an insecure fashion and inject malware into the connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This is one reason why the Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Tor Project started the development of HTTPS Everywhere, which is included in Tor Browser.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As more information is revealed about global mass surveillance and criminals stealing personal information, the use of HTTPS security on all websites is becoming increasingly important regardless of the type of Internet connection being used.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Even though metadata about individual pages that a user visits might not be considered sensitive, when aggregated it can reveal a lot about the user and compromise the user's privacy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Deploying HTTPS also allows the use of HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 (and their predecessors SPDY and QUIC), which are new HTTP versions designed to reduce page load times, size, and latency.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] It is recommended to use HTTP Strict Transport Security (HSTS) with HTTPS to protect users from man-in-the-middle attacks, especially SSL stripping.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS should not be confused with the seldom-used Secure HTTP (S-HTTP) specified in RFC 2660.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As of April 2018, 33.2% of Alexa top 1,000,000 websites use HTTPS as default and 70% of page loads (measured by Firefox Telemetry) use HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As of June 2025, 71.2% of the Internet's 150,000 most popular websites have a secure implementation of HTTPS (up from 58.4% in December 2022), However, despite TLS 1.3's release in 2018, adoption has been slow, with many still remaining on the older TLS 1.2 protocol.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Most browsers display a warning if they receive an invalid certificate.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Older browsers, when connecting to a site with an invalid certificate, would present the user with a dialog box asking whether they wanted to continue.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Newer browsers display a warning across the entire window.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Newer browsers also prominently display the site's security information in the address bar.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Extended validation certificates show the legal entity on the certificate information.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Most browsers also display a warning to the user when visiting a site that contains a mixture of encrypted and unencrypted content.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Additionally, many web filters return a security warning when visiting prohibited websites.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, opining that "In an ideal world, every web request could be defaulted to HTTPS", has provided an add-on called HTTPS Everywhere for Mozilla Firefox, Google Chrome, Chromium, and Android, which enables HTTPS by default for hundreds of frequently used websites.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Forcing a web browser to load only HTTPS content has been supported in Firefox starting in version 83.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Starting in version 94, Google Chrome is able to "always use secure connections" if toggled in the browser's settings.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Prior to version 117, Google Chrome displayed a lock icon in the address bar, which has since been replaced by a "tune" icon.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Many users believe that a lock icon implies a website is safe, ignoring other security concerns.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The security of HTTPS is that of the underlying TLS, which typically uses long-term public and private keys to generate a short-term session key, which is then used to encrypt the data flow between the client and the server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] X.509 certificates are used to authenticate the server (and sometimes the client as well).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As a consequence, certificate authorities and public key certificates are necessary to verify the relation between the certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] While this can be more beneficial than verifying the identities via a web of trust, the 2013 mass surveillance disclosures drew attention to certificate authorities as a potential weak point allowing man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] An important property in this context is forward secrecy, which ensures that encrypted communications recorded in the past cannot be retrieved and decrypted should long-term secret keys or passwords be compromised in the future.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Not all web servers provide forward secrecy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] For HTTPS to be effective, a site must be completely hosted over HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Additionally, cookies on a site served through HTTPS must have the secure attribute enabled.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] On a site that has sensitive information on it, the user and the session will get exposed every time that site is accessed with HTTP instead of HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS URLs begin with "https://" and use port 443 by default, whereas HTTP URLs begin with "http://" and use port 80 by default.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTP is not encrypted and thus is vulnerable to man-in-the-middle and eavesdropping attacks, which can let attackers gain access to website accounts and sensitive information, and modify webpages to inject malware or advertisements.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS is designed to withstand such attacks and is considered secure against them (with the exception of HTTPS implementations that use deprecated versions of SSL).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTP operates at the highest layer of the TCP/IP model—the application layer; as does the TLS security protocol (operating as a lower sublayer of the same layer), which encrypts an HTTP message prior to transmission and decrypts a message upon arrival.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Strictly speaking, HTTPS is not a separate protocol, but refers to the use of ordinary HTTP over an encrypted SSL/TLS connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS encrypts all message contents, including the HTTP headers and the request/response data.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] With the exception of the possible CCA cryptographic attack described in the limitations section below, an attacker should at most be able to discover that a connection is taking place between two parties, along with their domain names and IP addresses.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] To prepare a web server to accept HTTPS connections, the administrator must create a public key certificate for the web server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This certificate must be signed by a trusted certificate authority for the web browser to accept it without warning.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The authority certifies that the certificate holder is the operator of the web server that presents it.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Web browsers are generally distributed with a list of signing certificates of major certificate authorities so that they can verify certificates signed by them.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] A number of commercial certificate authorities exist, offering paid-for SSL/TLS certificates of a number of types, including Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Let's Encrypt, launched in April 2016, provides free and automated service that delivers basic SSL/TLS certificates to websites.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] According to the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Let's Encrypt will make switching from HTTP to HTTPS "as easy as issuing one command, or clicking one button." The majority of web hosts and cloud providers now leverage Let's Encrypt, providing free certificates to their customers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The system can also be used for client authentication in order to limit access to a web server to authorized users.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] To do this, the site administrator typically creates a certificate for each user, which the user loads into their browser.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Normally, the certificate contains the name and e-mail address of the authorized user and is automatically checked by the server on each connection to verify the user's identity, potentially without even requiring a password.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] An important property in this context is perfect forward secrecy (PFS).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Possessing one of the long-term asymmetric secret keys used to establish an HTTPS session should not make it easier to derive the short-term session key to then decrypt the conversation, even at a later time.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Diffie–Hellman key exchange (DHE) and Elliptic-curve Diffie–Hellman key exchange (ECDHE) are in 2013 the only schemes known to have that property.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] In 2013, only 30% of Firefox, Opera, and Chromium Browser sessions used it, and nearly 0% of Apple's Safari and Microsoft Internet Explorer sessions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] TLS 1.3, published in August 2018, dropped support for ciphers without forward secrecy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As of February 2019, 96.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 52.1% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As of July 2023, 99.6% of web servers surveyed support some form of forward secrecy, and 75.2% will use forward secrecy with most browsers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, for example because the secrecy of the private key has been compromised.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Newer versions of popular browsers such as Firefox, Opera, and Internet Explorer on Windows Vista implement the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) to verify that this is not the case.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The browser sends the certificate's serial number to the certificate authority or its delegate via OCSP (Online Certificate Status Protocol) and the authority responds, telling the browser whether the certificate is still valid or not.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The CA may also issue a CRL to tell people that these certificates are revoked.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] CRLs are no longer required by the CA/Browser forum, nevertheless, they are still widely used by the CAs.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Most revocation statuses on the Internet disappear soon after the expiration of the certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] SSL (Secure Sockets Layer) and TLS (Transport Layer Security) encryption can be configured in two modes: *simple* and *mutual*.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] In simple mode, authentication is only performed by the server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The mutual version requires the user to install a personal client certificate in the web browser for user authentication.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] In either case, the level of protection depends on the correctness of the implementation of the software and the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] SSL/TLS does not prevent the indexing of the site by a web crawler, and in some cases the URI of the encrypted resource can be inferred by knowing only the intercepted request/response size.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This allows an attacker to have access to the plaintext (the publicly available static content), and the encrypted text (the encrypted version of the static content), permitting a cryptographic attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Because TLS operates at a protocol level below that of HTTP and has no knowledge of the higher-level protocols, TLS servers can only strictly present one certificate for a particular address and port combination.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] In the past, this meant that it was not feasible to use name-based virtual hosting with HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] A solution called Server Name Indication (SNI) exists, which sends the hostname to the server before encrypting the connection, although older browsers do not support this extension.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Support for SNI is available since Firefox 2, Opera 8, Apple Safari 2.1, Google Chrome 6, and Internet Explorer 7 on Windows Vista.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] A sophisticated type of man-in-the-middle attack called SSL stripping was presented at the 2009 Blackhat Conference.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The attacker then communicates in clear with the client.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This prompted the development of a countermeasure in HTTP called HTTP Strict Transport Security.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] HTTPS has been shown to be vulnerable to a range of traffic analysis attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Traffic analysis attacks are a type of side-channel attack that relies on variations in the timing and size of traffic in order to infer properties about the encrypted traffic itself.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Traffic analysis is possible because SSL/TLS encryption changes the contents of traffic, but has minimal impact on the size and timing of traffic.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] In May 2010, a research paper by researchers from Microsoft Research and Indiana University discovered that detailed sensitive user data can be inferred from side channels such as packet sizes.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The researchers found that, despite HTTPS protection in several high-profile, top-of-the-line web applications in healthcare, taxation, investment, and web search, an eavesdropper could infer the illnesses/medications/surgeries of the user, his/her family income, and investment secrets.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The fact that most modern websites, including Google, Yahoo!, and Amazon, use HTTPS causes problems for many users trying to access public Wi-Fi hot spots, because a captive portal Wi-Fi hot spot login page fails to load if the user tries to open an HTTPS resource.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Several websites, such as NoSSL.sh, guarantee that they will always remain accessible by HTTP.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Netscape Communications created HTTPS in 1994 for its Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Originally, HTTPS was used with the SSL protocol.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] The original SSL protocol was developed by Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] As SSL evolved into Transport Layer Security (TLS), HTTPS was formally specified by RFC 2818 in May 2000.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] Google announced in February 2018 that its Chrome browser would mark HTTP sites as "Not Secure" after July 2018.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/https] This move was to encourage website owners to implement HTTPS, as an effort to make the World Wide Web more secure.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The HTTP **`Strict-Transport-Security`** response header (often abbreviated as HSTS) informs browsers that the host should only be accessed using HTTPS, and that any future attempts to access it using HTTP should automatically be upgraded to HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Additionally, on future connections to the host, the browser will not allow the user to bypass secure connection errors, such as an invalid certificate.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] HSTS identifies a host by its domain name only.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The time, in seconds, that the browser should remember that a host is only to be accessed using HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If this directive is specified, the HSTS policy applies to all subdomains of the host's domain as well.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] See Preloading Strict Transport Security for details.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] When using `preload`, the `max-age` directive must be at least `31536000` (1 year), and the `includeSubDomains` directive must be present.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The `Strict-Transport-Security` header informs the browser that all connections to the host must use HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Although it is a response header, it does not affect how the browser handles the current response, but rather how it makes future requests.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] When an HTTPS response includes the `Strict-Transport-Security` header, the browser adds the host's domain name to its persistent list of HSTS hosts.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If the domain name is already in the list, the expiration time and `includeSubDomains` directive are updated.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The host is identified only by its domain name.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] HSTS applies to all ports of the host, regardless of what port was used for the request.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Before loading an `http` URL, the browser checks the domain name against its HSTS hosts list.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If the domain name is a case insensitive match for an HSTS host or is a subdomain of one that specified `includeSubDomains`, then the browser replaces the URL scheme with `https`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If the URL specifies port 80, the browser changes it to 443.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Any other explicit port number remains unchanged, and the browser connects to that port using HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If a TLS warning or error, such as an invalid certificate, occurs when connecting to an HSTS host, the browser does not offer the user a way to proceed or "click through" the error message, which would compromise the intention of strict security.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Every time the browser receives a `Strict-Transport-Security` header, it updates the host's HSTS expiration time by adding `max-age` to the current time.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Using a fixed value for `max-age` can prevent HSTS from expiring, as each subsequent response will push the expiration farther into the future.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If the `Strict-Transport-Security` header is missing in a response from a host that previously sent one, the previous header remains in effect until its expiration time.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] This only takes effect once the browser makes a secure request and receives the response header.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] By design, you cannot disable HSTS over insecure HTTP.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The `includeSubDomains` directive instructs the browser to apply a domain's HSTS policy to its subdomains as well.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] An HSTS policy for `secure.example.com` with `includeSubDomains` also applies to `login.secure.example.com` and `admin.login.secure.example.com`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] But it does not apply to `example.com` or `insecure.example.com`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Each subdomain host should include `Strict-Transport-Security` headers in its responses even if the superdomain uses `includeSubDomains`, because a browser may contact a subdomain host before the superdomain.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] For example, if `example.com` includes the HSTS header with `includeSubDomains`, but all existing links go directly to `www.example.com`, the browser will never see `example.com`'s HSTS header.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Therefore, `www.example.com` also should send HSTS headers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The browser stores the HSTS policy for each domain and subdomain independently, regardless of the `includeSubDomains` directive.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If both `example.com` and `login.example.com` send HSTS headers, the browser stores two separate HSTS policies, and they can expire independently.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If `example.com` used `includeSubDomains`, then `login.example.com` remains covered if either one of the policies expires.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If `max-age=0`, `includeSubDomains` has no effect, since the domain that specified `includeSubDomains` is immediately deleted from the HSTS hosts list; this does not delete separate HSTS policies of each subdomain.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If the host accepts insecure HTTP requests, it should respond with a permanent redirect (such as status code `301`) having an `https` URL in the `Location` header.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The redirect must not include the `Strict-Transport-Security` header since the request used insecure HTTP but the header must be sent via HTTPS only.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] After the browser follows the redirect and makes a new request using HTTPS, the response should include the `Strict-Transport-Security` header to ensure that future attempts to load an `http` URL will use HTTPS immediately, without requiring a redirect.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] One weakness of HSTS is that it does not take effect until the browser has made at least one secure connection to the host and received the `Strict-Transport-Security` header.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] If the browser loads an insecure `http` URL prior to knowing that the host is an HSTS host, the initial request is vulnerable to network attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Since the URL scheme is `http` and the browser does not have it in its HSTS hosts list, the connection uses insecure HTTP.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The server responds with a `301 Moved Permanently` redirect to `https://example.com/`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The browser makes a new request, this time using HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The response, made via HTTPS, includes the header: `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains` The browser remembers `example.com` as an HSTS host, and that it specified `includeSubDomains`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] A few weeks later, the user is at the airport and decides to use the free Wi-Fi.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] But unknowingly, they connect to a rogue access point running on an attacker's laptop.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The user opens `http://login.example.com/`.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Because the browser remembers `example.com` as an HSTS host and the `includeSubDomains` directive was used, the browser uses HTTPS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The attacker intercepts the request with a fake HTTPS server, but does not have a valid certificate for the domain.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The browser displays an invalid certificate error, and does not allow the user to bypass it, thus preventing them from giving their password to the attacker.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] Google maintains an HSTS preload service.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] By following the guidelines and successfully submitting your domain, you can ensure that browsers will connect to your domain only via secure connections.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] While the service is hosted by Google, all browsers are using this preload list.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] However, it is not part of the HSTS specification and should not be treated as official.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] All present and future subdomains will be HTTPS for a `max-age` of 1 year.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] This blocks access to pages or subdomains that can only be served over HTTP.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] A `max-age` of 1 year is the minimum value accepted for HSTS preloading.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] The following example uses 2 years, which is the value shown in the example header on https://hstspreload.org.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/strict-transport-security] In the following example, `max-age` is set to 2 years, and is suffixed with `preload`, which is necessary for inclusion in all major web browsers' HSTS preload lists, like Chromium, Edge, and Firefox.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/x-content-type-options] The HTTP **`X-Content-Type-Options`** response header indicates that the MIME types advertised in the `Content-Type` headers should be respected and not changed.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/x-content-type-options] The header allows you to avoid MIME type sniffing by specifying that the MIME types are deliberately configured.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/x-content-type-options] Site security testers usually expect this header to be set (and that the `Content-Type` header is correctly set for all resources).
[src:http-strict-transport-security/x-content-type-options] Blocks a request if the request destination is of type `style` and the MIME type is not `text/css`, or of type `script` and the MIME type is not a JavaScript MIME type.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/x-content-type-options] It also prevents MIME type sniffing for all other response types, causing the browser to use the declared `Content-Type` without examining the response content.
[src:http-strict-transport-security/x-content-type-options] In particular it prevents a browser from treating a response as `text/html` when it is loaded in a browsing context and the `Content-Type` header is absent or indicates a non-HTML type.
